Subject:    network node pointers
From:       <a href="?a=95837783700005&r=1&w=2">Mark Lottor &lt;MKL () SRI-NIC ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198705">1987-05-28 3:00:14</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926873&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926873&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

A very common missing RR in name servers are the so called network
node pointers.  These can be used to locate gateways, among other things.

If you have the standard name to number and number to name RR's for
gateways in your name servers zone files, you should make sure you
also have the network node pointer.

For example, if the GW.CSL.SRI.COM gateway has as one of it's 
addresses 128.18.1.1 then in your IN-ADDR.ARPA zone file for
that net you should also have an RR specifying:
   
18.128.IN-ADDR.ARPA.		PTR	GW.CSL.SRI.COM.

And of course one for each network the gateway is on.
-------

